Note:
Runtime condition-variable API — the public condition-coordination object for
the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. The actual wait/wake mechanism is the
completed cross-platform synchronization facade (sync_core), which itself
delegates to the per-architecture OS futex / ulock / SRW primitives. This
module does NOT re-implement the wait or notify mechanism; it wraps the
sync_core condvar handle in a runtime RuntimeCondVar object and adds the
semantics a runtime contract requires that the raw facade does not provide:

  - MUTEX PAIRING: a condition variable is meaningless without an associated
    mutex. Every wait atomically releases a held mutex, blocks until notified,
    and re-acquires the mutex before returning. The caller passes the
    RuntimeMutex object (from mutex.runa). This module extracts that mutex's
    underlying sync_core handle (stored at RuntimeMutex offset 0) and hands the
    raw handle to the facade, so the runtime object layer of the condvar and
    the runtime object layer of the mutex compose without either knowing the
    other's internals beyond the published handle offset.
  - STANDARDIZED STATUS CODES: every entry point returns a CONDVAR_* status so
    callers branch on a single, documented contract rather than the facade's
    raw 1/0 platform results. The facade reports 1 for a successful wake, and
    0 for a timeout on the bounded wait (the Windows SRW path returns the BOOL
    directly — nonzero wake, zero timeout — and the futex / ulock / umtx paths
    follow the same nonzero-is-success convention); this layer translates those
    into CONDVAR_OK and CONDVAR_ERR_TIMEOUT.
  - POISONING: a coordinator that detects an unrecoverable error in the data
    protected by the paired mutex marks the condition variable poisoned, so
    waking threads can inspect condvar_is_poisoned and decide whether to
    recover or abort. This mirrors the poison model of the runtime mutex and
    keeps the two cooperating objects symmetric.

RuntimeCondVar layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  handle    — the sync_core condvar handle (the real wait queue)
    offset 8:  poisoned  — 0 healthy, 1 poisoned
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: RuntimeCondVar object layout
Constant RT_CONDVAR_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE as Integer is 0
Constant RT_CONDVAR_OFF_POISONED as Integer is 8

Note:
Offset of the underlying sync_core handle inside a RuntimeMutex object. This
matches mutex.runa's RuntimeMutex layout (RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE is 0), and is the
single point of coupling between the condvar object layer and the mutex object
layer: a wait reads the paired mutex's sync_core handle from this offset and
passes it to the facade.
:End Note
Constant RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE as Integer is 0

Note: Facade success convention — sync_core reports 1 for a successful wake
Constant SYNC_SUCCESS as Integer is 1
Note: Facade timeout convention — the bounded wait reports 0 when the deadline expires
Constant SYNC_TIMEOUT as Integer is 0

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime condition-variable API
Constant CONDVAR_OK as Integer is 0
Constant CONDVAR_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant CONDVAR_ERR_POISONED as Integer is 0 minus 2
Constant CONDVAR_ERR_WAIT_FAILED as Integer is 0 minus 3
Constant CONDVAR_ERR_TIMEOUT as Integer is 0 minus 4

Process called "condvar_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a runtime condition variable. Mechanism (the OS wait queue) comes
    from sync_core; this layer adds the poison flag and a stable object identity
    callers hold and pair with a RuntimeMutex.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 16-byte RuntimeCondVar, create the underlying sync_core
    condvar, store its handle, and initialize the poison flag to healthy (0).
    On any allocation/creation failure, release whatever was acquired and
    return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one sync_core condvar_create (which allocates its
    own control block and an OS wait word). Cold path: done once per condvar.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cv be proc allocate from Memory with RT_CONDVAR_SIZE
    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let handle be proc condvar_create from Sync
    If handle is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with cv
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE, handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return cv
End Process

Process called "condvar_wait" takes cv as Integer, m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically release the paired mutex, block until another thread signals or
    broadcasts this condition variable, then re-acquire the mutex before
    returning. The mutex must be held by the caller on entry and is held again
    on return.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Validate both the condvar object and the mutex object. Read this condvar's
    sync_core handle (offset 0) and the paired RuntimeMutex's sync_core handle
    (RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE), then delegate the atomic release/wait/re-acquire to
    sync_core condvar_wait. The facade reports 1 on a successful wake; any other
    result means the wait did not complete normally and is surfaced as
    CONDVAR_ERR_WAIT_FAILED.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core condvar_wait: a futex / ulock / SRW sleep that parks the
    thread until notified, bracketed by the facade's mutex release and
    re-acquire. No busy-waiting.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null condvar or null mutex returns CONDVAR_ERR_NULL without touching
    memory or the wait queue. On return (CONDVAR_OK or CONDVAR_ERR_WAIT_FAILED)
    the paired mutex is held again and the caller owns the obligation to release
    it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If m is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let cv_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE
    Let mutex_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    Let r be proc condvar_wait from Sync with cv_handle, mutex_handle
    If r is not equal to SYNC_SUCCESS:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_WAIT_FAILED
    End If
    Return CONDVAR_OK
End Process

Process called "condvar_timed_wait" takes cv as Integer, m as Integer, timeout_us as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bounded variant of condvar_wait: release the paired mutex and wait until
    either the condition is notified or the timeout elapses, then re-acquire the
    mutex. Callers that must make forward progress instead of blocking
    indefinitely use this entry point and branch on CONDVAR_ERR_TIMEOUT.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Validate both objects, extract the condvar's sync_core handle (offset 0) and
    the paired RuntimeMutex's sync_core handle (RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE), then
    delegate to sync_core condvar_timed_wait with the microsecond timeout. The
    facade returns 1 when woken by a signal/broadcast and 0 when the deadline
    expires; map those to CONDVAR_OK and CONDVAR_ERR_TIMEOUT respectively, and
    treat any other result as CONDVAR_ERR_WAIT_FAILED.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core condvar_timed_wait: a timed futex / ulock / SRW sleep. Adds
    deadline setup to condvar_wait's cost; still no busy-waiting.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null condvar or null mutex returns CONDVAR_ERR_NULL without touching the
    wait queue. On every non-null return the paired mutex is held again and the
    caller owns the obligation to release it, including on the timeout path.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If m is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let cv_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE
    Let mutex_handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    Let r be proc condvar_timed_wait from Sync with cv_handle, mutex_handle, timeout_us
    If r is equal to SYNC_SUCCESS:
        Return CONDVAR_OK
    End If
    If r is equal to SYNC_TIMEOUT:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_TIMEOUT
    End If
    Return CONDVAR_ERR_WAIT_FAILED
End Process

Process called "condvar_signal" takes cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake exactly one thread waiting on this condition variable. Used when a
    single waiter can make progress on the state change the signaller just
    published.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the sync_core handle and delegate to sync_core condvar_signal, which
    advances the wait sequence and wakes one parked waiter. Signalling a
    condvar with no waiters is a well-defined no-op at the facade, so the only
    failure surfaced here is a null object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core condvar_signal: an atomic sequence bump plus a single futex /
    ulock / SRW wake.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns CONDVAR_ERR_NULL. Should be called while holding the
    paired mutex so the state change is published before a waiter is released.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE
    proc condvar_signal from Sync with handle
    Return CONDVAR_OK
End Process

Process called "condvar_broadcast" takes cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake every thread waiting on this condition variable. Used when a state
    change may let more than one waiter make progress, or when the specific
    waiters that can proceed are not known.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the sync_core handle and delegate to sync_core condvar_broadcast, which
    advances the wait sequence and wakes all parked waiters. Broadcasting a
    condvar with no waiters is a well-defined no-op at the facade, so the only
    failure surfaced here is a null object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core condvar_broadcast: an atomic sequence bump plus a single
    wake-all futex / ulock / SRW operation. Woken threads then contend for the
    paired mutex one at a time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns CONDVAR_ERR_NULL. Should be called while holding the
    paired mutex so the state change is published before the waiters are
    released.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with handle
    Return CONDVAR_OK
End Process

Process called "condvar_is_poisoned" takes cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report whether a coordinator flagged the state guarded by the paired mutex
    as inconsistent. A thread woken from a wait checks this before trusting the
    shared data.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the poison flag (1 poisoned, 0 healthy).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_POISONED
End Process

Process called "condvar_poison" takes cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mark the condition variable poisoned. A coordinator that detects an
    unrecoverable failure in the protected state calls this (then typically
    broadcasts) so waking threads are warned the data may be inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding the paired mutex so the flag is published
    before any waiter observes it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_POISONED, 1
    Return CONDVAR_OK
End Process

Process called "condvar_clear_poison" takes cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Clear the poison flag after a caller has repaired the protected state,
    returning the condition variable to normal service.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding the paired mutex, after the inconsistent
    state has actually been repaired.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return CONDVAR_OK
End Process

Process called "condvar_destroy" takes cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the OS wait queue and free the runtime object. Must not be called
    while any thread is waiting on the condition variable.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core condvar_destroy (which frees the facade control block
    and the OS wait word), then deallocate the RuntimeCondVar object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core condvar_destroy plus one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns CONDVAR_ERR_NULL. Destroying a condvar with active
    waiters is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return CONDVAR_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cv, RT_CONDVAR_OFF_HANDLE
    proc condvar_destroy from Sync with handle
    proc deallocate from Memory with cv
    Return CONDVAR_OK
End Process
